      "content": "The function can be optimized by iterating one less time, as the loop `(i, j)` is equivalent to all possible pairs `(j, i)`. This reduces the time complexity from O(n^2) to O(n^2 / 2). \n\n```python\ndef heavy_sum(n):\n    total = 0\n    n /= 2  # divide by 2 to find the symmetry\n    for i in range(int(n)):\n        total += (i * (n - i - 1)) % 123  # Handles case where j=i and adds a termination condition\n    return total\n```\nAlternatively, you can take advantage of `math.comb(n, 2)` and vectorized operations with libraries like `numpy` to further enhance performance.\n\nYou can use numpy for an even more efficient and faster solution:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef heavy_sum(n):\n    return np.sum(np.connmat(123, n)) % 123\n```",
